    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-09-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-09-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="190"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d190">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">103.<gloss target="#t_AEC1"
                    >AEC</gloss>/9–2650</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. <persName type="from"
                            >Lucius D. Battle</persName>, Special Assistant to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>,<note n="1" xml:id="d190fn1">Acheson and Bevin were chairmen of
                            their respective delegations to the Fifth Session of the United Nations
                            General Assembly which convened in New York on September 19.</note>]
                            <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-09-26">September 26,
                        1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Mr. Acheson</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Bevin</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Barclay<note n="2" xml:id="d190fn2">R. E. Barclay, private
                                secretary to Mr. Bevin.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Battle</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Mr. Bevin asked Mr. Acheson about developments in the field of atomic energy with
                    particular reference to continuance of the discussions which were held in the
                    past between the United States and the British in this field. Mr. Acheson said
                    that he thought some progress was being made and that he had recently obtained
                    an expression from the Department of Defense and the Atomic Energy Commission in
                    favor of resuming the discussions. Mr. Acheson said that he thought it was
                    important to handle this as quietly as possible. He recommended against the
                    British sending over anyone for the discussions who was as well known as Sir
                    Roger Makins whose presence attracted some comment and attention. Mr. Acheson
                    said that he would be in touch with Sir Oliver Franks on this field.</p>
            </div>
